{"title_page": "NeXT RISC Workstation", "text_new": "#REDIRECT [[NeXT#Second generation]]\n\n{{R cat shell |\n  {{R from subtopic}}\n  {{R to section}}\n}}\n", "text_old": "The '''NeXT RISC Workstation''', or '''NRW''', was an unreleased [[computer workstation]] designed by [[NeXT]] during the early 1990s as a successor to the [[m68k]]-based [[NeXTcube]] and [[NeXTstation]]. Initially the NRW was to be based on the Motorola [[88110]] [[microprocessor]], but due to a lack of confidence in Motorola's commitment to the 88k architecture, it was later redesigned around dual [[PowerPC 601]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hardware was great while it lasted | work=NeXTWORLD| | author=Simson L. Garfinkel | date=March 1993| url=http://www.simson.net/ref/NeXT/nextworld/NextWorld_Extra/93.03.Mar.NWE/93.03.Mar.NWExtra21.html| accessdate=2007-04-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Canon to buy NeXT factory, design center| work=NeXTWORLD | author=Dan Lavin | date=March 1993|url=http://www.simson.net/ref/NeXT/nextworld/NextWorld_Extra/93.03.Mar.NWE/93.03.Mar.NWExtra07.html | accessdate=2007-04-30}}</ref>  Pre-production motherboards and enclosures were produced, but the NRW did not enter production before NeXT exited the hardware market in 1993.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nextcomputers.org/NeXTfiles/Images/Rare_NeXT_Hardware/NRW-NeXT_RISC_Workstation/ Photos of NRW motherboard and enclosure]\n\n[[Category:NeXT]]\n[[Category:Computer workstations]]\n\n{{compu-hardware-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Smuckola", "label": "safe", "comment": "this content is already identical to that of part of the new target section so no content needs to be migrated, and there is no particular hope of expanding this subject of a prototype", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=NeXT_RISC_Workstation&redirect=no"}
{"title_page": "Anonymous pipe", "text_new": "{{See also|Pipeline (Unix)|Pipeline (software)}}\nIn [[computer science]], an '''anonymous pipe''' is a [[simplex channel|simplex]] [[FIFO (computing and electronics)|FIFO]] communication channel that may be used for one-way [[interprocess communication]] (IPC). An implementation is often integrated into the [[operating system]]'s file [[Input/output|IO]] subsystem. Typically a parent program opens anonymous pipes, and creates a new process that inherits the other ends of the pipes, or creates several new processes and arranges them in a [[Pipeline (software)|pipeline]].\n\n[[Full-duplex]] (two-way) communication normally requires two anonymous pipes.\n\n[[Pipeline (Unix)|Pipelines]] are supported in most popular operating systems, from [[Unix]] and [[DOS]] onwards, and are created using the \"<code>|</code>\" character in many shells.\n\n== Unix ==\n\n[[Pipeline (Unix)|Pipelines]] are an important part of many traditional [[Unix]] applications and support for them is well integrated into most [[Unix-like]] operating systems. Pipes are created using the <code>pipe</code> [[system call]], which creates a new pipe and returns a pair of [[file descriptor]]s referring to the read and write ends of the pipe. Many traditional Unix programs are designed as [[Filter (Unix)|filters]] to work with pipes.\n\n== Microsoft Windows ==<!-- This section is linked to from [[Inter-process communication]]. Do not rename. -->\nLike many other device IO and IPC facilities in the [[Windows API]], anonymous pipes are created and configured with API functions that are specific to the IO facility. In this case <code>CreatePipe</code> is used to create an anonymous pipe with separate handles for the read and write ends of the pipe. Read and write IO operations on the pipe are performed with the standard IO facility API functions <code>ReadFile</code> and <code>WriteFile</code>.\n\nOn [[Microsoft Windows]], reads and writes to anonymous pipes are always blocking.<ref>{{cite web| title=Anonymous Pipe Operations | publisher=MSDN | url=http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/aa365141.aspx | accessdate=2010-02-27 | quote=Asynchronous (overlapped) read and write operations are not supported by anonymous pipes.}}</ref> In other words, a read from an empty pipe will cause the calling thread to wait until at least one byte becomes available or an [[end-of-file]] is received as a result of the write handle of the pipe being closed. Likewise, a write to a full pipe will cause the calling thread to wait until space becomes available to store the data being written. Reads may return with fewer than the number of bytes requested (also called a ''short read'').\n\nNew processes can inherit handles to anonymous pipes in the creation process.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Named pipe]]\n* [[Anonymous named pipe]]\n* [[Pipeline (Unix)]]\n\n== References ==\n* Hart, Johnson M. ''Windows System Programming, Third Edition.'' Addison-Wesley, 2005. {{ISBN|0-321-25619-0}}\n* {{cite web| title=pipe(7) - Linux man page | url=http://linux.die.net/man/7/pipe | accessdate=2010-02-27| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100323183044/http://linux.die.net/man/7/pipe| archivedate= 23 March 2010 | url-status= live}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Inter-process communication}}\n\n[[Category:Inter-process communication]]\n", "text_old": "{{See also|Pipeline (Unix)|Pipeline (software)}}\nIn [[computer science]], an '''anonymous pipe''' is a [[simplex channel|simplex]] [[FIFO (computing and electronics)|FIFO]] communication channel that may be used for one-way [[interprocess communication]] (IPC). An implementation is often integrated into the [[operating system]]'s file [[Input/output|IO]] subsystem. Typically a parent program opens anonymous pipes, and creates a new process that inherits the other ends of the pipes, or creates several new processes and arranges them in a [[Pipeline (software)|pipeline]].\n\n[[Full-duplex]] (two-way) communication normally requires two anonymous pipes.\n\n[[Pipeline (Unix)|Pipelines]] are supported in most popular operating systems, from [[Unix]] and [[DOS]] onwards, and are created using the \"<code>|</code>\" character in many shells.\n\n== Unix ==\n\n[[Pipeline (Unix)|Pipelines]] are an important part of many traditional [[Unix]] applications and support for them is well integrated into most [[Unix-like]] operating systems. Pipes are created using the <code>pipe</code> [[system call]], which creates a new pipe and returns a pair of [[file descriptor]]s referring to the read and write ends of the pipe. Many traditional Unix programs are designed as [[Filter (Unix)|filters]] to work with pipes.\n\n== Microsoft Windows ==<!-- This section is linked to from [[Inter-process communication]]. Do not rename. -->\nLike many other device IO and IPC facilities in the [[Windows API]], anonymous pipes are created and configured with API functions that are specific to the IO facility. In this case <code>CreatePipe</code> is used to create an anonymous pipe with separate handles for the read and write ends of the pipe. Read and write IO operations on the pipe are performed with the standard IO facility API functions <code>ReadFile</code> and <code>WriteFile</code>.\n\nOn [[Microsoft Windows]], reads and writes to anonymous pipes are always blocking.<ref>{{cite web| title=Anonymous Pipe Operations | publisher=MSDN | url=http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/aa365141.aspx | accessdate=2010-02-27 | quote=Asynchronous (overlapped) read and write operations are not supported by anonymous pipes.}}</ref> In other words, a read from an empty pipe will cause the calling thread to wait until at least one byte becomes available or an [[end-of-file]] is received as a result of the write handle of the pipe being closed. Likewise, a write to a full pipe will cause the calling thread to wait until space becomes available to store the data being written. Reads may return with fewer than the number of bytes requested (also called a ''short read'').\n\nNew processes can inherit handles to anonymous pipes in the creation process.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Named pipe]]\n* [[Anonymous named pipe]]\n* [[Pipeline (Unix)]]\n\n== References ==\n* Hart, Johnson M. ''Windows System Programming, Third Edition.'' Addison-Wesley, 2005. {{ISBN|0-321-25619-0}}\n* {{cite web| title=pipe(7) - Linux man page | url=http://linux.die.net/man/7/pipe | accessdate=2010-02-27| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100323183044/http://linux.die.net/man/7/pipe| archivedate= 23 March 2010 | url-status= live}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{IPC}}\n\n[[Category:Inter-process communication]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anonymous_pipe"}
